Q4 What is the difference between On‑Demand, Reserved, and Spot instances?

In Amazon EC2, pricing models determine how you pay for the instances you run.
The three common pricing models are On-Demand, Reserved, and Spot Instances.

On-Demand instances:
-------------------
let you pay only for the compute time you use, with no long-term commitment.
Key Points
-----------
Pay per hour or second
No upfront payment
Can start or stop anytime
Most flexible option

When to Use
-------------
Development or testing environments
Short-term workloads
Applications with unpredictable traffic

Reserved Instances
------------------
Reserved instances give a large discount if you commit to using EC2 for 1 or 3 years.
Key Points:-
Up to 70–75% cheaper than On-Demand
Long-term commitment (1 or 3 years)
Can choose partial or full upfront payment
Best for stable workloads
When to Use

Production systems
Long-running backend servers
Applications with predictable usage
Spot Instances
---------------
Spot instances allow you to use unused AWS compute capacity at very low prices.

Up to 90% cheaper
AWS can terminate the instance anytime
Not suitable for critical workloads

When to Use

Batch processing
Data analysis
Machine learning training
Jobs that can be interrupted


