Q6 What is the purpose of a security group in EC2?

A security group in EC2 acts as a virtual firewall that controls inbound and outbound traffic to the instance.
It allows us to define which ports, protocols, and IP addresses can access the EC2 server to ensure secure communication.
The main purpose is to protect the EC2 server by allowing only specific traffic.
It controls:
Inbound Rules → Traffic coming into the server
Outbound Rules → Traffic going out of the server

| Port | Protocol | Purpose            |
| ---- | -------- | ------------------ |
| 22   | SSH      | Connect to server  |
| 80   | HTTP     | Web traffic        |
| 443  | HTTPS    | Secure web traffic |
| 3000 | Custom   | Node.js app        |

Q7  How do you configure inbound and outbound rules?

In my project, we configured EC2 security group inbound rules to allow SSH access on port 22 from our IP,
HTTP/HTTPS traffic for users, and port 3000 for our Node.js API. For outbound rules, we allowed HTTPS traffic so the server could call external APIs and services.

1️⃣ Configure Inbound Rules (Incoming Traffic)
| Type       | Port | Source    | Purpose               |
| ---------- | ---- | --------- | --------------------- |
| SSH        | 22   | My IP     | Developer SSH access  |
| HTTP       | 80   | 0.0.0.0/0 | Public website access |
| HTTPS      | 443  | 0.0.0.0/0 | Secure website        |
| Custom TCP | 3000 | 0.0.0.0/0 | Node.js API           |

2️⃣ Configure Outbound Rules (Outgoing Traffic)

| Type        | Port | Destination | Purpose             |
| ----------- | ---- | ----------- | ------------------- |
| HTTP        | 80   | 0.0.0.0/0   | Call external APIs  |
| HTTPS       | 443  | 0.0.0.0/0   | Secure API calls    |
| All Traffic | All  | 0.0.0.0/0   | Default AWS setting |


Q8 What happens if you lose your private key? What is the workaround?

If we lose the private key of an EC2 instance, AWS cannot recover it because the private key is not stored by AWS. 
The common workaround is to stop the instance, detach its root EBS volume, attach it to another EC2 instance, 
modify the authorized_keys file to add a new key, then reattach the volume and start the instance.
Another modern approach is using AWS Systems Manager Session Manager to access the instance without SSH.


Q9 How do you scale EC2 instances?

EC2 instances can be scaled using vertical scaling (changing the instance type) or
horizontal scaling (adding multiple instances using Auto Scaling and a Load Balancer).
Add multiple EC2 instances to handle more traffic using Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling and a Elastic Load Balancing.

Q10 What is Auto Scaling? How have you used it?

Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling automatically adds or removes EC2 instances based on traffic or CPU usage.
It helps maintain high availability and performance while reducing cost.
How I Used It (Practical Example)

I created an Auto Scaling Group for my Amazon EC2 instances.
Configured minimum = 2, maximum = 5 instances.
Set a rule: if CPU usage > 70%, launch a new instance.
Attached the instances to Elastic Load Balancing to distribute traffic.
When traffic decreases, extra instances are automatically terminated.

Q11 What is a Load Balancer (ALB/ELB) and how did you configure it with EC2?
A Load Balancer distributes incoming traffic across multiple EC2 instances to ensure high availability.
I configured an Application Load Balancer, created a target group with EC2 instances, 
added listeners for HTTP/HTTPS, and attached the instances so traffic is evenly distributed.

Q12 What is EBS? Difference between EBS and Instance Store?
EBS is persistent block storage for EC2 instances, meaning data remains even after the instance stops. 
Instance Store is temporary storage, and data is lost if the instance stops or terminates.

Q13 How do you increase EBS volume size?
To increase EBS volume size, modify the volume from the AWS console, increase the storage size, and then extend the filesystem inside the EC2 instance.

Q14 What is VPC? Why do EC2 instances need VPC subnets?
Amazon Virtual Private Cloud (VPC) is a private network in AWS where you launch resources like Amazon EC2 instances.
It allows you to control IP addresses, subnets, routing, and security.

A subnet divides a VPC into smaller networks.
EC2 instances must be placed in a subnet to:

Assign a private IP address
Control network access (public or private)
Manage security and routing

Example:

Public Subnet → EC2 accessible from the internet
Private Subnet → EC2 only accessible internally

